<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - opinion]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/opinion <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/opinion" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - opinion - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 22 日星期六 02:07:17 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[‘Antiracists’ vs. Academic Freedom]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>一位加州教授就新的 DEIA 绩效评估提起诉讼。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590081930629635118"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590081930629635118"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 6:40 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/daymon-johnson-lawsuit-california-community-colleges-bakersfield-deia-faculty-education-7fc2763e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822093?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kirby Lee/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>佛罗里达州州长<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">罗恩·德桑蒂斯</a>的批评者认为，他在试图根除公立大学的“觉醒”方面做得太过分了，但看看加利福尼亚州，看看如果不加以遏制，学术群体思维将会走向何方。贝克斯菲尔德的一位历史学教授本月提起的一份法律诉讼称，他的社区学院的表现和终身教职审查被用来迫使教师在课堂上采用觉醒的进步价值观。</p><p>戴蒙·约翰逊 (Daymon Johnson) 自 1993 年起就在贝克斯菲尔德学院 (Bakersfield College) 工作。正如他所说，三个月前，为 116 个校区的 180 万名学生提供服务的加州社区学院修改了其规定，要求员工必须拥护多元化、公平、包容性和无障碍 (DEIA) 的原则。规定称：“教职员工应采用反映 DEIA 和反种族主义原则的教学、学习和专业实践。”学校必须“高度重视 DEIA 在员工评估和任期审查方面的能力”。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>最后一项政策的详细基线解释很快就分发给了教师，包括贝克斯菲尔德学院的教师。根据约翰逊先生诉讼中作为证据所附的副本，该文件<a href="https://go.boarddocs.com/ca/cccchan/Board.nsf/files/C8FVAS7FD746/$file/dei-competencies-criteria-a11y.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">称</a>：“本文件中提供的 DEI 能力旨在定义所有加州社区学院 (CCC) 员工必须表现出的技能、知识和行为。”以下是它列出的一些作为教职员工成功标志的项目：</p><p> • “促进并融合 DEI 和反种族主义教育学。”</p><p> • “开发并实施一种教学法和/或课程，以促进种族意识和交叉视角。”</p><p> • “为 DEI 和反种族主义研究和学术做出贡献。”</p><p> • “阐明了 DEI 和反种族主义的重要性和影响，作为该机构更大使命的一部分。”</p><p> • “倡导并推进 DEI 和反种族主义目标和举措。”</p><p> • “通过参与 DEI 团体、委员会或社区活动来领导 DEI 和反种族主义工作，以促进系统性和文化变革，以缩小公平差距并支持少数群体。”</p><p> • “参与对个人成长和对 DEI 承诺的连续自我评估，并承认任何内在的个人偏见和种族优越或自卑。”</p><p>约翰逊先生反对这一切，并在言论自由研究所的帮助下提起诉讼。他的文件称：“约翰逊教授无法在不违背良心和放弃学术自由的情况下满足基于州财政大臣 DEIA 能力的 DEIA 标准。” “约翰逊教授教授的几乎所有内容都违反了新的 DEIA 要求——不仅未能推进 DEIA 和反种族主义意识形态，而且还批评了它们。”</p><p>他不想改变他的“强调研究‘真、善、美’的古典教育学。”他不想进行 DEIA 的“自我反思”，“他认为这是类似宗教的，只不过是新马克思主义关于种族的再教育。”他不想“阐明”反种族主义信条，他认为这“与贝克斯菲尔德学院的使命和美国国家理想背道而驰，即不歧视并为所有人提供平等机会，无论一个人皮肤中的黑色素如何。”</p><h4> ***</h4><p>约翰逊先生强调，DEIA 的这一举措并不是试图在课堂上接触来自不同背景的学生的良性指示。这是一个激进的政治项目。他引用了加州社区学院发布的<a href="https://www.cccco.edu/-/media/CCCCO-Website/Files/dei/deia-glossay-of-terms-a11y.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">DEIA 官方术语表</a>：</p><p> • 反种族主义者“明白种族主义是普遍存在的，并且已经融入到所有社会结构中。”另外：“人们要么是反种族主义者，要么是种族主义者。自称‘不是种族主义者’的人否认存在的不平等和种族问题。”</p><p> • 色盲“不再强调或忽视种族和民族，而种族和民族是一个人身份和生活经历的很大一部分。”建议的同义词是“颜色回避”，这是更好的，因为它“通过使用失明作为无知的隐喻，避免将残疾人描述为有问题或有缺陷。”</p><p> • 优点“从表面上看似乎是对学术成就和资格的中立衡量标准；然而，优点植根于白人的意识形态中，并维护基于种族的结构性不平等。”</p><p>神圣斗争会议。如果说学术自由有什么意义的话，那就是政府不能让历史教授向学生强行灌输这种政治垃圾。法院可以向约翰逊先生和他的同事澄清这一点。但政治问责制也很重要，就像佛罗里达州一样。这是加州人真正想要从州高等教育体系中得到的吗？ </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=79574680-0106-44EF-A6E4-6BC8AF5022CB&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdaymon-johnson-lawsuit-california-community-colleges-bakersfield-deia-faculty-education-7fc2763e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">尽管努力压制他的声音，2024 年民主党总统候选人小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪 (Robert F. Kennedy Jr.) 在联邦政府审查制度听证会上仍捍卫言论自由和第一修正案。图片：彭博新闻/盖蒂图片社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 22:40:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/daymon-johnson-lawsuit-california-community-colleges-bakersfield-deia-faculty-education-7fc2763e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/daymon-johnson-lawsuit-california-community-colleges-bakersfield-deia-faculty-education-7fc2763e<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>工作场所歧视/虐待</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>种族主义/仇外心理</category><category>社会问题</category><category>大学学院</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>加州社区学院</category><category>加州社区学院</category><category>戴蒙·约翰逊</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>工作场所歧视</category><category>虐待</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>种族主义</category><category>仇外心理</category><category>社会问题</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Student Loan ‘Payment Shock’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在拜登的忍耐期间，许多借款人承担了其他债务。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590097913546862310"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590097913546862310"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 6:37 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/student-loan-payments-transunion-report-student-debt-biden-administration-c9923d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822098?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>经过三年半的缓期后，学生贷款支付终于将于十月恢复。借款人对他们突然不得不节省开支感到震惊。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TRU" class="company-name">TransUnion</a>本周的一份报告显示，大流行病的长期暂停可能鼓励许多借款人积累更多债务。</p><p>国会于 2020 年 3 月暂停学生贷款的付款和应计利息七个月，以帮助可能在大流行初期失业的借款人。特朗普和拜登政府一再延长约 4000 万借款人的宽限期，尽管他们的财务状况因新冠转移支付而总体有所改善。</p><p>许多借款人利用每月的学生贷款储蓄来增加支出。现在，他们惊讶地发现自己必须再次还款，而媒体则大肆报道借款人因必须优先偿还债务而感到不安的故事。</p><p>但许多借款人还承担了额外的债务。 TransUnion 的数据显示，大约 53% 的学生贷款消费者增加了银行信用卡债务，36% 的消费者申请了新的汽车贷款，15% 的消费者增加了抵押贷款和无担保个人贷款。只要借款人不必偿还学生贷款，他们就有能力偿还其他债务。</p><p> TransUnion 指出：“当借款人试图重新调整每月预算以适应这种新付款时，他们将经历付款冲击。”大约四分之一的学生贷款借款人每月还款额超过 400 美元，从 10 月份开始，6.6% 的学生贷款借款人每月还款额将超过 1,000 美元。</p><p>暂停还款使拥有昂贵研究生学位的借款人受益最大，但他们基本上不会从拜登总统将每月还款额限制在可自由支配收入的 5% 的提议中受益。一个可能的结果是，未来几个月其他债务的违约率可能会上升，尤其是可变利率无担保贷款。</p><p>学生贷款延期已经让纳税人损失了超过 2000 亿美元，贷款机构现在可能也必须为此付出代价。拜登总统多次延长暂停付款的时间，以收买年轻人的选票，但不良的激励措施会产生后果，现在该法案即将到期。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=968EF75F-0B77-4A6F-A6C4-A5C16DD54614&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fstudent-loan-payments-transunion-report-student-debt-biden-administration-c9923d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：随着保守派不再信任联邦调查局，进步自由派不再信任当地警察部队，我们所依赖的保护我们的人正在离开执法部门，犯罪率不断上升。图片：彭博新闻社/祖玛出版社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 22:37:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/student-loan- payments-transunion-report-student-debt-biden-administration-c9923d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/student-loan- payments-transunion-report-student-debt-biden-administration-c9923d<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>评级机构</category><category>金融服务</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>高等教育费用</category><category>教育</category><category>个人财务</category><category>助学贷款</category><category>大学学院</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>职业教育</category><category>环联</category><category>特鲁</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>高等教育费用</category><category>教育</category><category>个人财务</category><category>助学贷款</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>职业教育</category><category>评级机构</category><category>金融服务</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Sheldon Whitehouse Ethics Mirror]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>民主党以另一场奇观推动最高法院法案。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590100160934253580"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590100160934253580"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 6:35 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/senate-democrats-supreme-court-ethics-bill-markup-judiciary-committee-sheldon-whitehouse-sandra-whitehouse-clarence-thomas-5eb17abf"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821212?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">罗德岛州参议员谢尔顿·怀特豪斯</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·布罗克斯坦/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>参议院民主党人这些天没有乐趣，除非他们攻击一位保守的最高法院法官，这使得周四对他们的司法“道德”法案的加价成为本季的事件。领导这一指控的是罗德岛州参议员谢尔登·怀特豪斯，他声称高等法院“被特殊利益集团所控制”。</p><p>正如预期的那样，在周四的司法委员会上，怀特豪斯提出了“免费假期”。但他也批评大法官们从他所谓的“协调前线团体之友”那里接收法庭之友简报，即智囊团和其他有勇气就悬而未决的案件发表意见的团体。怀特豪斯说：“一些朋友已经收到了各方的报酬。” “其他人掩盖了特殊利益以影响法律。”</p><p>咳咳，影响法律是所有法庭之友陈述都试图做的事情。他们来自某一特定问题的各个方面。看待这一问题的一种方式是，将其视为健康的公民社会中的一场激烈辩论。怀特豪斯先生更愿意看到阴谋。他说：“从统计数据来看，这些右翼前线团体的某些法官以他们的方式做出裁决，这一记录令人震惊。”保守派智囊团提出保守派法学家最终采纳的论点，真的令人惊讶吗？</p><p>怀特豪斯还特别针对克拉伦斯·托马斯法官，他的妻子吉妮·托马斯是一位保守派活动家。在周四的听证会上，他表示，基于“他对妻子叛乱活动的了解以及他何时知道”，托马斯法官应该在涉及 1 月 6 日骚乱的案件中被要求回避，同时建议高等法院应该“做出事实裁决”。</p><p>这是对托马斯大法官的又一次党派攻击，但这很奇怪，尤其是来自怀特豪斯先生，他知道与职业女性结婚是什么感觉。他的妻子桑德拉·怀特豪斯（Sandra Whitehouse）与包括海洋保护协会在内的团体一起研究环境问题，而这些组织恰好与他的国会利益有交叉。</p><p> 2022 年，怀特豪斯先生发起了《蓝色地球法案》，海洋保护协会在致国会的一封信中推动了该法案。 2019-20 年，怀特豪斯先生发起了《拯救我们的海洋法案》，这是海洋保护协会的另一项优先事项。怀特豪斯夫人确实担任该组织的政策顾问和顾问。这些点是否可以与另一个阴谋论联系起来？如果名字不同，怀特豪斯先生可能会说是。但我们假设怀特豪斯先生和夫人对地球有着共同的兴趣。</p><p>司法委员会以党派路线投票以 11 比 10 的结果通过了最高法院道德法案。它不会去任何地方，也不应该去任何地方，但这从来都不是目标。这一奇观是民主党人对大法官的诚信提出质疑并成为立法者头条新闻的另一个平台。主席迪克·德宾 (Dick Durbin) 表示，道德改革是最高法院“恢复信心的关键第一步”。他的真正意思是，这是削弱法院权力的第一步，法院不再充当第二个进步立法机构。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=52B0CFB0-0E03-4C90-9E19-A15E110CDD96&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fsenate-democrats-supreme-court-ethics-bill-markup-judiciary-committee-sheldon-whitehouse-sandra-whitehouse-clarence-thomas-5eb17abf&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">回顾与展望：美国国税局特工加里·沙普利和约瑟夫·齐格勒在宣誓后表示，他们调查亨特·拜登的尝试面临着司法部前所未有的干预。司法部长梅里克·加兰和特拉华州联邦检察官大卫·韦斯会做出回应吗？图片：彭博新闻/盖蒂图片社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 22:35:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/senate-democrats-supreme-court-ethics-bill-markup-judiciary-committee-sheldon-whitehouse-sandra-whitehouse-clarence-thomas-5eb17abf</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/senate-democrats-supreme-court-ethics-bill-markup-judiciary-committee-sheldon-whitehouse-sandra-whitehouse-clarence-thomas-5eb17abf<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>突击</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>最高法院</category><category>谢尔顿·怀特豪斯</category><category>桑德拉·怀特豪斯</category><category>突击</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The U.K. Elections Are a Political Wake-Up Call]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>保守党的两次失败是对里希·苏纳克(Rishi Sunak)关于经济增长的警告。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590101771185566714"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590101771185566714"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 6:26 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-parliamentary-elections-tories-boris-johnson-rishi-sunak-labour-party-bac316ba"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822092?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">英国首相里希·苏纳克</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Martyn Wheatley/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>有时地方选举会讲述一个更大的故事，英国本周举行的三场议会补选也是如此。在包括前首相<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/boris-johnson">鲍里斯·约翰逊</a>在内的现任议员辞职后，执政的保守党正在努力保住三个席位。保守党输掉了其中的两场比赛，但在第三场比赛中却苦苦挣扎。</p><p>自2010年以来最严重的失败是在保守党控制的北约克郡选区。在四年前的上次选举中，他们的候选人以大约20,000票获胜。本周，反对党工党以约 4,000 票的优势翻转了席位。类似的逆转也发生在英格兰西部，保守党自 2015 年以来一直占据该席位，上次以 19,000 票左右的优势赢得席位，现在却被中间派自由民主党以 11,000 票的优势夺走。</p><p>经济像乌云一样笼罩着选举，民意调查显示， <a href="https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/tories-uxbridge-south-ruislip-by-election-win-2023-hrbq33ddt" target="_blank" class="icon none">经济悲观情绪比 2008 年以来的任何时候都要严重。</a>其中一个信息是，总理里希·苏纳克 (Rishi Sunak) 的计划——痛苦的增税以试图稳定政府预算，而没有其他经济增长计划——是失败者。保守党在非法移民等其他问题上的任何优势都无法在明年的全国大选中拯救他们。</p><p>保守党也不能指望工党这次会犯很多错误。约翰逊在 2019 年与前工党领袖杰里米·科尔宾 (Jeremy Corbyn) 的竞选中赢得了历史性胜利，后者的极左经济和文化观点甚至冒犯了许多长期工党选民。科尔宾的继任者基尔·斯塔默(Keir Starmer)通过削减工党大笔支出、高额税收的野心，使工党再次成为安全的选择。</p><p>需要注意的是环境政策，工党本周以微弱优势赢得了第三个席位。保守党在约翰逊位于伦敦郊区的旧选区以不到 500 票的优势赢得了胜利，而 2019 年的领先优势超过 7,000 票。就连获胜的保守党候选人也承认，如果不是针对工党的抗议选票反对伦敦市长扩大对在该市行驶的旧车征收环保税的计划，他就会落败。</p><p>双重警告是，右翼政党需要向选民提供可信的经济增长信息，而左翼政党则需要缓和其极端的绿色议程。即将到来的英国及其他地区的选举将取决于哪一方能最快吸取教训。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=87D9068E-77D8-4079-9F23-679C8A6B3081&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-k-parliamentary-elections-tories-boris-johnson-rishi-sunak-labour-party-bac316ba&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">经过一场强调军事优先事项与文化问题的辩论后，众议院共和党人于 7 月 14 日通过了《国防授权法案》(NDAA)。图片：Getty Images 综合：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 22:26:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/uk-parliamentary-elections-tories-boris-johnson-rishi-sunak-labour-party-bac316ba</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/uk-parliamentary-elections-tories-boris-johnson-rishi-sunak-labour-party-bac316ba<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济增长/衰退</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>保守党</category><category>民工党</category><category>托利党</category><category>里希·苏纳克</category><category>鲍里斯·约翰逊</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济增长</category><category>经济衰退</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Hollywood Strike’s Big Risk Is a ‘Nanny’ Without a Plan]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>当演员工会的影响力很低时，演员工会就因采取激进的姿态而被迫罢工。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590101731792399408"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590101731792399408"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/holman-w-jenkinsjr"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BI571_jenkin_AM_20180807123815.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">小</span><span class="author" itemprop="name">霍尔曼·W·詹金斯</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 5:34 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hollywood-strikes-big-risk-is-a-nanny-without-a-plan-union-film-streaming-bde3c89f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821548?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">弗兰·德雷舍 (Fran Drescher)、邓肯·克拉布特里-爱尔兰 (Duncan Crabtree-Ireland) 和 SAG-Aftra 工会成员，7 月 13 日在洛杉矶。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克·布莱克/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>当演员工会老板、90 年代情景喜剧《保姆》的主演弗兰·德雷舍 (Fran Drescher) 几周前宣称 SAG-Aftra 与制片厂之间的谈判“非常有成效”时，她的一线同事却不想听。</p><p>梅丽尔·斯特里普（Meryl Streep）和詹妮弗·劳伦斯（Jennifer Lawrence）等签名者在一封充满罢工热情的信中警告称，“成员们可能已经准备好做出领导层没有做出的牺牲。”德雷舍女士意识到自己的地位受到威胁，于是把自己变成了德伐日夫人，参加《愤怒的葡萄》的试镜。自从工会应对好莱坞大停工事件以来，就看不到任何策略。</p><p>世界上有一些松散的东西——一些杆菌——为了自身的满足而寻求彻底的破坏。编剧和演员最后一次齐聚是在 1960 年，为了分享电视蓬勃发展的新机会。最新的情况发生之际，流媒体泡沫已经破裂，网络和有线电视正在自由落体，娱乐巨头已经开始缩小规模并进行大规模裁员。</p><p>就谈判计划而言，目前并没有什么“杠杆作用”。</p><p> “演员和编剧都表示，向流媒体的转型让他们蒙受了损失，”彭博新闻解释道。但这就像在桶干了之后想要获得更多的啤酒一样。</p><p>如果德雷舍女士精力充沛的蒸发是为了隐藏一个深层次的阴谋，那么它隐藏得很好。 “我们正在成为一个非常贪婪的实体的受害者，”她说，显然指的是三年前她的成员以 74% 的投票通过的合同。</p><p>她的工会弥漫着一种“摇尾巴”的困境。该公会可能拥有 160,000 名持卡会员，但只有 27% 的人对其上一份合同进行了投票。一项外部<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/shortcuts/2019/jun/05/only-2-per-cent-of-actors-make-a-living-how-do-you-become-one-of-them" target="_blank" class="icon none">研究</a>发现，在电视和电影中出现的人中，只有 2% 实际上以此谋生。该协会本身只会说 87% 的会员收入不足（每年 26,000 美元），没有资格获得健康保险，尽管 Drescher 女士最近透露大多数会员的收入不到 10,000 美元。</p><p>其影响并不乐观。严肃认真、高薪的专业人士正在为了“熟练工”（德雷舍女士最喜欢的词）的利益而暂停自己的职业生涯，对他们来说，罢工可能是一种乐趣，就像偶尔在电影片场呆上一天一样。</p><p>当然，有些人正在追求终生的抱负，但其中许多“幕后演员”（以前被称为“临时演员”）几乎没有真正参与其中。他们是最有可能因不恰当的面部表情或手势而搞砸昂贵镜头的人。然而，工会代表他们投入了谈判资金，以阻止电影制片人在付费拍摄后对图像进行数字修复。</p><p>这是电影制作未来的现实愿景吗？不，如果电影制作逃离洛杉矶地区，前往经济更合理的气候，“熟练工”将失去立足点。</p><p>好莱坞对电影娱乐业的准垄断，顺便将演员和编剧行会的古朴习俗奉为全球产业，这并不是自然法则。尽管金属丝城的成本不断膨胀，但制作电影的技术能力却变得越来越便宜。可以在 iPhone 上<a href="https://www.indiewire.com/features/general/movies-shot-on-iphones-unsane-tangerine-shorts-1201941565/#:~:text=When%20Sean%20Baker's%20breakout%20indie,a%20trio%20of%20iPhone%205s." target="_blank" class="icon none">制作和编辑</a>故事片。一个九年级学生就能制作一部带有图形的太空歌剧，让《2001》相形见绌。很快，业余爱好者将可以访问一屋子基于类似 ChatGPT 的大型语言模型的脚本医生。</p><p>对人工智能的恐慌可能适合工会在缺乏行动计划的情况下在其成员中培养的神风特攻队心态。谈判中泄露的信息表明，双方实际上都看到了美元迹象，只是在争夺新工具的控制权。</p><p>德雷舍女士的一个头脑风暴显然是由她父亲<a href="https://variety.com/2023/biz/news/sag-actor-strike-contract-sticking-points-1235670826/" target="_blank" class="icon none">建议的</a>，这是一种第三方算法，可以根据社交媒体的提及来估计一部节目对于流媒体订阅者来说可能值多少钱。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>了解更多商业世界</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/of-evs-and-heat-waves-range-anxiety-tesla-emissions-climate-7baa0f7d?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">电动汽车和热浪</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 18 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-musk-zuckerberg-cage-match-twitter-threads-free-speech-ad-revenue-social-media-profit-e05ba039?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">马斯克与扎克伯格的笼式比赛已于</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 14 日</span>开始</li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-is-saving-joe-from-huntergate-biden-2024-ukraine-election-8ea7c62f?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">特朗普将拜登从亨特笔记本电脑丑闻中拯救出来</a><span class="date">2023 年 6 月 30 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>这里的想法是怀旧的，即创建一个相当于曾经从重播联合组织中赚取的“剩余”演员的流媒体版本。它也是所有非传单中的非传单，因为流媒体对其收视率数据赋予了专有价值。如果需要一种新的风险分担模式（而且可能是这样），即在节目受到订户欢迎之前扣留大笔资金，那么该行业很可能在没有德雷舍女士父亲帮助的情况下找到自己的出路。</p><p>然而，缺乏任何其他工会结局的迹象。演员约翰·库萨克已成为德雷舍女士众多吵闹的助手之一。他在推特上表示，贪婪是指别人不想给他钱。他想要钱并不是贪婪。也许公会的策略超出了我的理解范围，但它的言辞和一大堆吐槽者根本没有表明任何策略。它确实说明了为什么如今好莱坞的这么多作品似乎对智商有挑战。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=48E03FE9-F0A5-41FB-8532-879C1D176E1F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhollywood-strikes-big-risk-is-a-nanny-without-a-plan-union-film-streaming-bde3c89f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">代表演员和编剧的电视和电影工会自 1960 年以来首次就 Netflix、Disney+ 和 Amazon Prime 等流媒体平台的更高薪酬等问题举行罢工。图片：祖马出版社/美联社/盖蒂图片社/路透社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 21:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hollywood-strikes-big-risk-is-a-nanny-without-a-plan-union-film-streaming-bde3c89f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hollywood-strikes-big-risk-is-a-nanny-without-a-plan-union-film-streaming-bde3c89f<category>好莱坞</category><category>作家</category><category>演员</category><category>罢工</category><category>联盟</category><category>电影</category><category>流媒体</category><category>电视</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>劳动争议</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>劳资纠纷</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Tense ‘Sunday Morning Breakfast’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>霍勒斯·皮平 (Horace Pippin) 1943 年的画作描绘了一个宁静的家庭聚会，但在令人愉悦的笔触之下却隐藏着对美国社会微妙而引人注目的批判<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11790807057722524561504589600800504709662"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818700?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">霍勒斯·皮平的《周日早餐》</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：圣路易斯艺术博物馆</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11790807057722524561504589600800504709662"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">朱迪思·H·多布津斯基</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 4:39 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-tense-sunday-morning-breakfast-7bae83cc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>霍勒斯·皮平的《周日早餐》（1943）散发着魅力。它以一种看似简单、直截了当的方式，捕捉到了一个黑人家庭在安息日共进晚餐的情景，这是在电视、周日营业时间和其他现代消遣方式被广泛采用之前的简单时代的珍贵时刻。然而，仔细观察，这幅由圣路易斯艺术博物馆拥有的画作却变得更加丰富。皮平静静地、敏锐地揭示了这个家庭的贫困状况，也许正因为如此，他暗示了表面之下隐藏着的家庭动态的紧张。</p><p>皮平也比他早年作为一名艺术家所表现的更加深刻。 1888 年出生于宾夕法尼亚州西切斯特，第一次世界大战期间，他在著名的第 369 步兵团“哈莱姆地狱战士”中服役，曾做过酒店搬运工和仓库工作。他从战斗中归来，身体残疾，右肩被狙击手击中，导致手臂部分瘫痪，并开始写作和插图他的战争回忆录作为治疗。 1925 年之后的某个时候，他开始作画，右手拿着画笔，用左臂移动它。起初，他并没有引起多少注意。但十几年后，随着公众开始关注自学成才的“民间”艺术家，NC Wyeth（著名插画家、安德鲁的父亲）在宾夕法尼亚州当地的一场艺术展上称赞了皮平的两幅画作。皮平的名气一下子爆了。</p><p>一年之内，现代艺术博物馆在 1938 年题为“流行绘画大师：欧洲和美国的现代原始画”的展览中展出了四幅皮平的油画，该展览还前往其他场馆展出。几家博物馆很快购买了他的作品，并与画廊一起举办了他的个展。比赛为他颁发了享有声望的奖项。收藏家们购买了他的画作，其中包括阿尔伯特·C·巴恩斯（Albert C. Barnes），他是费城巴恩斯基金会的创始人，他们称赞这些画作简单而天真。 （1940 年左右，皮平在巴恩斯学院参加了艺术课程，但他很快就离开了，更喜欢自学。）</p><p>在他的职业生涯中，皮平创作了多个主题：战争、种族主义、圣经故事、肖像画、静物画和描绘非裔美国人生活的风俗画。 20世纪90年代中期，宾夕法尼亚美术学院组织了一场他的作品巡回展览，展览的标题恰如其分地用了他自己的话：“我讲述我的心”。 2015 年在布兰迪万艺术博物馆举办的另一场展览以皮平解释其艺术的一句话的最后一部分作为标题：“我按照它本来的样子和我看到它的方式来画它。”</p><p> 《周日早餐》符合这两个特点。皮平在书中回忆起厨房里的场景。他的简单环境似乎是一片宁静的海洋，部分是由于其大部分柔和的色调，部分是由于其令人赏心悦目的对称性。左侧的双镶板米色门与右侧的双门蓝色橱柜相平衡。父亲的白衬衫与母亲飘逸的白色连衣裙相呼应，两个孩子也都穿白色的衣服。绿色的窗帘从画作的中心垂直切下，由黑色长凳、栗色桌布和黑色炉子暗示的较细的水平线所抵消。</p><p>不过，这个时刻并不是一成不变的。皮平通过画出炉子上水壶冒出的蒸汽、母亲走向耐心等待食物的孩子们、父亲穿上鞋子来增添生活气息。观众很容易想象皮平确实目睹了这样的场面，并且正在展示他所看到的一切。</p><p>为了将自己的心融入到场景中，皮平使用了一些细节，比如母亲穿的带图案的大手帕和围裙、简陋的钩形地毯、发光的炉子和靠近橱柜的尴尬的小架子，架子上有时钟和台灯。他用破损的椅背、裸露的墙板和破烂的窗帘暗示了这个家庭的贫困。在门的上方，他画了一个倒置的马蹄铁，这是一个充满希望的象征，旨在为这个家庭带来所需的运气。他把父亲放在椅子的边缘，与其他人分开，并描绘他的眼睛没有看着他的家人，而是警惕地看着他的左边。也许担心？赤着脚的母亲没有从孩子们身上抬起头来，孩子们似乎正在分享一盘食物，并且热切地等待着。</p><p>皮平在这里以一种低调的方式营造出一种家庭氛围，就像埃德加·德加在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/detonating-the-nuclear-family-11596832968?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">《贝莱利家族》</a> （1858-59 年，约 1867 年修订）中巧妙描绘的紧张的家庭动态一样巧妙（并让人想起）。</p><p> 《周日早餐》就像皮平著名的其他家庭场景一样，从来没有陷入伤感。它也不是说教的。皮平以自己平衡的方式将注意力集中在美国社会的一部分上，而这些部分在很大程度上被他那个时代的其他杰出艺术家所忽视。这是最微妙的社会评论。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -多发性硬化症。多布津斯基为《华尔街日报》和其他出版物撰写有关艺术的文章。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 20:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-tense-sunday-morning-breakfast-7bae83cc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-tense-sunday-morning-breakfast-7bae83cc<category>艺术评论</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Biden Would Deny Me Health Insurance]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>政府试图将客户从短期计划转移到成本更高的奥巴马医保，这将导致许多人放弃医保。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590086030284425138"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590086030284425138"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">维多利亚·埃尔德利</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 4:04 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-would-deny-me-health-insurance-obamacare-exchange-premium-short-term-ab25d8d9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821546?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7 月 7 日，乔·拜登总统在白宫发表讲话。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Chris Kleponis/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>两年前，我开始第一次寻找健康保险。我即将年满 26 岁，那时我将被父母的保险取消，而我和我的丈夫都没有资格通过雇主立即获得保险。经过几周的狩猎，我购买了一份短期健康保险计划。它具有我需要的覆盖范围和负担能力。</p><p>本月，拜登总统宣布了一项<a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/07/07/fact-sheetpresident-biden-announces-new-actions-to-lower-health-care-costs-and-protect-consumers-from-scam-insurance-plans-and-junk-fees-as-part-of-bidenomics-push/#:~:text=Under%20the%20new%20rules,%20if,made%20by%20the%20previous%20administration." target="_blank" class="icon none">法规</a>，将严格限制短期健康保险计划的期限。他称其为“垃圾保险”，但事实并非如此。大约<a href="https://waysandmeans.house.gov/new-biden-admin-regulation-threatens-access-to-affordable-health-care-for-millions/" target="_blank" class="icon none">150 万人</a>依赖短期计划，正是因为它们提供了真正的价值。</p><p>考虑一下我在 2021 年购买的计划。作为一名健康的年轻女性，我不需要通过奥巴马医改交易所提供的昂贵计划。我选择了一个短期计划，月费比最便宜的交换计划低 200 多美元。</p><p>该计划承保我每月唯一的处方，虽然有 10,000 美元的免赔额，但我并不介意。奥巴马医改计划也有同样高的免赔额，无论如何，我只需要基本的东西。如果发生灾难，该计划可承保高达 250,000 美元的医疗费用。我和丈夫用这些积蓄来支付搬家费用以及购买新房的首付。我们在 2022 年更换了承保范围，但如果需要的话，我很乐意将计划延长 36 个月。</p><p>拜登先生正在破坏像我这样的人的灵活性。他的规定将短期计划限制为三个月而不是一年。它还将延期期限限制为四个月而不是三年。随着计划到期，人们将通过奥巴马医改交换寻求新的保险。那时他们就会发现我两年前发现的情况：不必要的保险价格天价。</p><p>这才是重点。拜登政府希望利用像我这样的年轻人的钱，让奥巴马医改看起来并不是一场彻底的灾难。即使有了我们的钱，奥巴马医改计划的费用仍然逐年增加，保费涨幅往往超过 10%。没有年轻人的钱，保费增长得更快。这可能会将交易所推入死亡螺旋，数百万人因价格过高而放弃奥巴马医改，导致价格进一步上涨。</p><p>拜登政府以帮助一些人的名义，却伤害了另一些人。据国会预算办公室称，那些目前有短期计划的人会发现“最便宜”的奥巴马医改计划的每月<a href="https://www.cbo.gov/system/files/2019-01/54915-New_Rules_for_AHPs_STPs.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">保费可能是其近 10 倍</a>。尽管拜登政府认为人们会支付这些虚高的价格，但许多人买不起。 2019 年，国会预算办公室估计， <a href="https://www.cbo.gov/system/files/2019-01/54915-New_Rules_for_AHPs_STPs.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">大约有 60 万人</a>宁愿没有保险也不愿支付奥巴马医改的疯狂价格。</p><p>这就是拜登新规则的<a href="https://thefga.org/research/biden-administrations-action-short-term-health-plans/" target="_blank" class="icon none">现实</a>：拥有良好健康保险的人将失去它，他们要么会找到不适合自己生活方式或钱包的更糟糕的计划，要么完全没有保险。两年前我购买健康保险时，我本来不必做出这样的选择，但拜登先生现在却把它强加给其他人。美国人仍然应该享有我所享有的同样的自由、灵活性和经济节省。</p><p><em>埃尔德利女士是政府问责基金会的营销总监。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=968EF75F-0B77-4A6F-A6C4-A5C16DD54614&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fbiden-would-deny-me-health-insurance-obamacare-exchange-premium-short-term-ab25d8d9&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：随着保守派不再信任联邦调查局，进步自由派不再信任当地警察部队，我们所依赖的保护我们的人正在抛弃执法部门，犯罪率不断上升。图片：彭博新闻社/祖玛出版社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 20:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-would-deny-me-health-insurance-obamacare-exchange-premium-short-term-ab25d8d9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-would-deny-me-health-insurance-obamacare-exchange-premium-short-term-ab25d8d9<category>健康保险</category><category>奥巴马医改</category><category>保费</category><category>交流</category><category>短期计划</category><category>规定</category><category>垃圾</category><category>价格</category><category>保险</category><category>非人寿保险</category><category>健康/医疗保险</category><category>金融服务</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category><category>保险</category><category>非人寿保险</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗保险</category><category>金融服务</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Hollywood Strikes Will Hurt Georgia]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>我的工作权利州热爱电影业，但不关心工会。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590098863792463970"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590098863792463970"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">布鲁斯·汤普森</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 4:03 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hooray-for-hollywood-boo-for-unions-georgia-writers-actors-strike-e1b9ad51"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821180?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7 月 17 日，SAG-Aftra 演员工会成员在亚特兰大举行集会。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：约翰·阿瑟·布朗/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><em>亚特兰大</em></p><p>佐治亚州凭借其优惠的税收优惠和地域多样性，已成为影视制作的热点。上个月的研究表明，桃州拥有全美增长最快的电影业。但美国作家协会和演员协会-美国电视和广播艺术家联合会的罢工正在震动娱乐业。作为佐治亚州的劳工专员，我可以告诉你们，这对我州的劳动力和经济的影响可能是毁灭性的。</p><p>佐治亚州是一个工作权州。这意味着它既不支持工会，也不歧视选择不加入工会的员工。我们相信甚至鼓励小企业所有权。正因为如此，企业已经从工会州迁往这里。我们非常乐意为电影业在佐治亚州工作提供激励措施，但我们不会让他们的工会危及我们的劳动力。</p><p>从美容业到酒店业再到交通运输，佐治亚州的几个依赖电影和电视制作的行业都因罢工而失业，这给许多已经因拜登总统领导下创纪录的通货膨胀而受到伤害的佐治亚州家庭带来了更多的不确定性。</p><p>罢工和工会活动令人沮丧，但我不能单独责怪电影业。拜登先生努力营造支持工会的信息，为这些团体提供勇气。在整个任期内，他自豪地声称自己是“历史上最支持工会的总统”。尽管他知道这些罢工对佐治亚州造成了怎样的损害，但他仍然支持这些工会。</p><p> He recently remarked to a crowd in Philadelphia that Republicans are “coming for your jobs.” To that I ask: What jobs will there be when the unions have taken control of US businesses? When forced dues and decreased competitiveness destroy America&#39;s job market, will we look back and be thankful for the union activists in the White House?</p><p> Since I moved to Georgia three decades ago, I&#39;ve seen firsthand how right-to-work culture and business laws have made it a great state to do business. If states like California and Massachusetts want to let unions run things, fine. But I can&#39;t sit idly by and let Mr. Biden&#39;s unions devastate our state&#39;s labor force. Georgians won&#39;t forget this.</p><p> <em>Mr. Thompson is Georgia&#39;s labor commissioner.</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=48E03FE9-F0A5-41FB-8532-879C1D176E1F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhooray-for-hollywood-boo-for-unions-georgia-writers-actors-strike-e1b9ad51&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">代表演员和编剧的电视和电影工会自 1960 年以来首次就 Netflix、Disney+ 和 Amazon Prime 等流媒体平台的更高薪酬等问题举行罢工。图片：祖马出版社/美联社/盖蒂图片社/路透社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 20:03:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hooray-for-hollywood-boo-for-unions-georgia-writers-actors-strike-e1b9ad51</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hooray-for-hollywood-boo-for-unions-georgia-writers-actors-strike-e1b9ad51<category>作家</category><category>演员</category><category>georgia</category><category> labor force</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>电影</category><category>电视</category><category>tax incentives</category><category> peach state</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Labor/Personnel</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>劳动争议</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>General Labor Issues</category><category>电影</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>labor</category><category> personnel</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>劳资纠纷</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>general labor issues</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category><category>媒体</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Doug Burgum, on the Record]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Excerpts from the Journal&#39;s July 10 editorial board meeting with the North Dakota governor and GOP presidential candidate. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590093930700259958"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590093930700259958"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 4:03 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/doug-burgum-on-the-record-north-dakota-china-energy-tech-2024-3f32b2ec"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820871?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Doug Burgum speaks in Salix, Iowa, July 19.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jerry Mennenga/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <strong>On his background in tech:</strong></p><p> Dad passed away when I was a freshman in high school. So my mom went back to work, widow with three kids. 。 。 。 And then when I was in my mid-20s, I had a bit of farm ground I got from my dad. I literally bet the farm on a software startup. 。 。 。 We went from sort of 10 STEM small-town kids to you know, fantastic, at the time, one of the top 10 IPOs on Nasdaq. We had a great run as a public company, very successful, and then we were acquired by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="">Microsoft</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> I stayed at Microsoft for seven years. 。 。 。</p><p> I retired from Microsoft in 2007, came back to North Dakota, and had three kids. I had been trying to do parenting and commuting to Seattle and all over the world. And I needed to spend more time on the parenting side and so came back but then started two other companies, one that was focused on trying to basically save downtown Fargo. It was going down and I knew from—we had now almost a 2,000-person campus at Microsoft in Fargo—that we had to have a community that was going to attract and retain young people, a community that was going to be vibrant and safe, and so got into, sort of backed into, historic building renovation and restoration. And then began to understand the economics of cities and mixed-use infill and all these things that public policy, we&#39;re driving or not driving in terms of how federal policy and federal incentives are actually subsidizing sprawl, creating uneconomic cities, driving up property taxes, affecting individuals in lower income groups.</p><p> Because a lot of these cities are being built—they&#39;re great if you&#39;ve got dual income and three cars, you can live in a city where each of your kids can drive to the high school that&#39;s here and the mall that&#39;s there or whatever. But it doesn&#39;t work very well for families that might not have those same economic means. So we got very interested in the economics of cities during that time period, and was one of the reasons in the end, why we decided to run for governor, but also started a venture business in North Dakota, investing in purpose-driven software companies.</p><p> <strong>On why he&#39;s running for president:</strong></p><p> We&#39;ve never had a candidate run for office who&#39;s got a background and understanding around technology, and understands how technology is changing every job in every industry more so than ever. 。 。 。</p><p> In both 2016 and 2020 we&#39;ve won by some of the largest margins of any gubernatorial races in the country. And we&#39;ve done that with an idea that we&#39;re basically running on the issues we&#39;re running on now. Economy, energy, national security—these are the things that if you get these right, these are the economic underpinnings and the security underpinnings that really enable America to reach its fullest potential. We talk about it in terms of the best of America, because we see that every day in places like North Dakota and places where we go where you can have two things happening simultaneously, great things happening with great companies in great communities with great nonprofits doing things that are really neighbors helping neighbors, and at the same time, you can have a federal government with a set of policies around the economy and around energy policy and around national security, which are all interrelated, completely going 180 degrees in the wrong direction. So that&#39;s what we&#39;re running on, because we care deeply about people, we know that we can make a difference.</p><p> <strong>On whether the US is in a cold war with China:</strong></p><p> Well, let me first say that I think it&#39;s odd that it&#39;s not being acknowledged, because when you think about the 1960s and &#39;70s, sort of the standard definition—if you&#39;ve got military aircraft dodging each other, if you&#39;ve got naval ships within 50 yards of each other, if you&#39;ve got spy balloons coming over the country, if you&#39;ve got a spy base going in Cuba, I mean, it seems like that would be the definition of a cold war unless we&#39;ve changed what it is.</p><p> I also see it as a governor because part of a cold war that didn&#39;t exist in the &#39;60s—today is also cyber war. And we&#39;re under cyber attack every day, the state of North Dakota, every day. Come and see our ops center—North Korea, Russia, China, Iran . 。 。 they&#39;re attacking our cities, our tribes, our universities, our K-12 districts every single day. 。 。 。</p><p> I mean, so I feel that we&#39;re on the front line of defense in a cyber war, and then no one actually says we&#39;re actually in a cyber war. I mean, why wouldn&#39;t we just say that? 。 。 。 When we have the two largest economies in the world, and they&#39;re incredibly intertwined, and then we have [Secretary of State Antony] Blinken going over and then [Treasury Secretary Janet] Yellen, I&#39;ve read everything that I can find written about these things, I haven&#39;t heard that Blinken even mentioned the word energy when he was there.</p><p> China is the world&#39;s largest importer of oil and gas—over 10 million barrels of oil a day. And I suppose maybe he can&#39;t bring up energy policy because back here, the de facto policy is we&#39;re going to shut down any fossil-fuel-based, carbon-based industry in America, as opposed to saying, “Hey, if we&#39;re a true energy superpower, to have a negotiation, internationally and economic statecraft, you have to have leverage somewhere in the negotiation.” 。 。 。</p><p> Some of our sanctions have been really absurd, because all we&#39;re doing is shifting who the suppliers are. Sometimes in those cases we might be affecting American farmers more than we were affecting the Chinese. Now we put sanctions on Russia, around oil and gas, belatedly, and so great. So they&#39;re, “Oh, we&#39;re really sticking into Russia, they&#39;re selling at a 20% off world market.” Well, who&#39;s buying it?中国。 I mean, the farmers I talk to in Iowa would like to buy their diesel tomorrow at 20% off for their tractors, but they&#39;re not getting a chance to do that. We&#39;re certainly not only just turning Russia into China&#39;s gas station, we&#39;re also giving China an economic advantage for manufacturing.</p><p> <strong>On China and the economy:</strong></p><p> When we look back at Russia, when they collapsed, at the size of their economy, I think it was less than $2 trillion, or something like that. I mean, it was like half the size of what healthcare is in America right now. Or it&#39;s the size of Texas or something, even today. So it&#39;s a very different thing. We could isolate them, and they could operate within the Soviet bloc. If we take a look at even right now with our allies in the Pacific, I think if you take the five—Japan, Philippines, South Korea, Australia and New Zealand—those five together are about half the size of the US economy. But the last time I checked, they were selling five or six times as much into China as we are. So we buy from China, but we don&#39;t sell to China. It would be great if they were dependent on us, as opposed to us dependent on them.</p><p> What they would buy from us, though, on the restrictions on technology is we should not be giving up things that allow us to have an advantage relative to innovation. Because that&#39;s how the American economy wins. 。 。 。</p><p> The first time I was in China was as a student in 1980. The first time I was there as an entrepreneur was 1989. I was on my way back from setting up Australia as the first Great Plains international partner. 。 。 。 On the way back, I swing through China. And I&#39;m told that there&#39;s this market where you can go to in Shenzhen where they sell software, US software. 。 。 。 So I go there and I walk in, and we&#39;re at like a 250-person company in Fargo, not selling outside of North America, and I said, “Hey, do you have Great Plains?” and they&#39;re like, “Sure.” And they walked me over and I can buy on a 5¼-inch floppy for $1—we were selling our stuff for $5,000 a module. For a buck, I could buy a copy of Great Plains in 1989. And so then along the entire pathway of my career in software, every company I&#39;ve been in, we&#39;ve never been able to establish a big business in China. And when you go there, your stuff is already there. 。 。 。</p><p> So stealing intellectual property is something that I&#39;ve lived with. And so in that sense, [China] can&#39;t be trusted. So we have to figure out whether its military defense, telecommunication and other advances and where we are with AI right now. The people that are calling for us to slow down AI development, you know, when I see that online, I&#39;m like, OK, well, that must be one of the 40% of the social media accounts that are Chinese bots saying we should slow down. Of course, they want us to slow down, right? We have a lead. And so we have to just keep pushing ahead on all these technologies.</p><p> <strong>On China and energy policy:</strong></p><p> I think we have to have energy be part of the discussion. 。 。 。 Supposedly we have an existential crisis. And you can never say the word climate without saying crisis. And now you can&#39;t say climate without existential crisis. I mean, those three words somehow have to go together. When, if we don&#39;t have baseload energy, no one&#39;s going to have air conditioning in Arizona and Florida. I mean, we know all these growth states that are like, oh, these red states are growing, and they have warmer latitudes, and we&#39;ve got the power to be able to supply them to allow them to have resilience in the current environment if it gets warmer or colder. Energy has to be the base.</p><p> So then some of these agreements that we&#39;re in, where we&#39;re going to reduce our emissions now, but China can keep building their CO2 emissions until 2035? I was checking, and they&#39;ve got 41 coal plants permitted. They&#39;re opening about one every two weeks in China. And they&#39;re doing that with 1980s technology, and they&#39;re not even doing it with the year 2000. It started with Obama, and Obama was saying, we&#39;re going to shut down the baseload energy industry, and we&#39;re specifically going after coal. How about you go after CO2? Isn&#39;t CO2 the problem or is coal the problem? 。 。 。</p><p> Where are the highest concentrations of rare-earth minerals in America? In some of the lignites in places like Wyoming, Montana and North Dakota. So we could do both, as opposed to this idea that somehow we&#39;re going to solve our climate problem by shutting down liquid fuels. We&#39;re going to go with EVs, but then we have to buy all of our rare-earth minerals from China? I mean, this is the most absurd thing. 。 。 。</p><p> You can&#39;t separate China policy from what they&#39;re calling climate policy—but I&#39;ll call it energy policy—because it makes it makes no economic sense. I mean, it&#39;s like economic poverty, manufacturing poverty, for our country to pursue what they&#39;re doing. 。 。 。 We can&#39;t shut down everything in the US and then allow everybody else to keep using old technology. Why aren&#39;t we selling the new clean technology from the United States? If you&#39;re really concerned about CO2, you would want to have every drop of energy produced in the United States. We do it cleaner, safer, better. It&#39;s so hypocritical—I mean, in North Dakota, we&#39;re 400,000 barrels of oil below where we were pre-Biden. 。 。 。</p><p> So part of the policies would have to be, if you were going to actually have national security, we would have to be able to provide US energy to all states in the lower 48. . 。 。 A Burgum administration policy would be sell energy to our allies, stop buying it from our enemies.</p><p> <strong>On media reports of China buying farmland in the North Dakota:</strong></p><p> Well, there&#39;s a lot of misinformation around that as well. Because in North Dakota, we have some of the strictest anti-corporate-farming laws in America. 。 。 。 I mean, literally you&#39;ve got to be second cousins or closer to be able to buy farmland and operate in North Dakota, super strict thing. So then every headline is, “China&#39;s buying farmland.” It&#39;s like, China can&#39;t buy farmland in North Dakota, it&#39;s against the law. They can&#39;t do it. They did buy some land inside the city limits of Grand Forks inside an ag-industrial park. 。 。 。 But in the current environment, it was just a complete no-go. And so the minute the Air Force said no, we said no, we&#39;re not doing this thing and we&#39;ll look for somebody else to come in and take over this kind of thing because there&#39;s obviously a business opportunity there.</p><p> <strong>On the culture wars:</strong></p><p> Well, I think . 。 。 they have nothing to do with being president of the United States. The 10th Amendment is very clear about what the federal government&#39;s role is, and what&#39;s not specifically for the federal government, that limited number of things is designated to the states or to the people. I mean, it&#39;s a one-sentence amendment in the Constitution that I believe is basically overstepped all the time, all the time, all the time.</p><p> And I&#39;ve seen it as, again, small business. medium business, governor, I&#39;ve seen the federal overreach. So <em>Dobbs</em> ? Support <em>Dobbs</em> —leave it up to the states. I was a candidate for not even 12 hours and the first question on CNN was how do you feel about signing a federal abortion amendment? I said I wouldn&#39;t sign it. 。 。 。 We said, it&#39;s up to the states, the states have to decide. What works for North Dakota is not going to work for California or New York, it doesn&#39;t even work for Minnesota, I mean, right next door. Two states can have very different approaches on some of these cultural issues. 。 。 。</p><p> I vetoed a book-banning bill. And if there&#39;s a parent in a small town that&#39;s got a concern about one book that was in the wrong section, they&#39;ve got options. They can decide not to go to the library, they can talk to the librarian, and if they don&#39;t get the right answer from the librarian, they can go to the library board and the library board&#39;s got a policy about how do you move a book from one section to another. But to pass a state law where you&#39;re going to criminalize librarians, and then we&#39;re going to have to have the library book police on what sections, that&#39;s going the wrong way, that&#39;s adding red tape, that&#39;s adding regulation. And if the Republican Party believes in freedom and responsibility and parental rights, and whatever, then, let&#39;s get it figured out and say some of this stuff, that would be state overreach. That one we were able to sustain.</p><p> These are hot topics. They matter deeply to some people. But we&#39;re running a race to get the federal government focused on the stuff that matters. And part of national security is border security. 。 。 。 Today there won&#39;t be a headline anywhere in the US, but there&#39;ll be another 330 people that die of overdoses today. If 300 people died in a plane crash, it&#39;d be in the news for the next month or a year. 。 。 。 We have to secure the border, No. 1. These are large criminal enterprises. I mean, there&#39;s big, big money, moving this amount of stuff. And when I say secure the border, it&#39;s not just build the wall. You build the wall, and then they can still fly a drone or an ultralight over the top of it in 10 seconds and drop enough fentanyl to kill everybody in New York City. And there&#39;s technology, there&#39;s ground sensors, there&#39;s things that we have to do, but there has to be a comprehensive approach. 。 。</p><p> So I just sort of feel like it&#39;s a failure of leadership at all levels. And explicitly, one of the things the federal government is supposed to do as part of their national security is actually secure the border. That&#39;s one of the things that the federal government is supposed to do, as opposed to, you know, weigh in on lots of things that aren&#39;t part of the job description.</p><p> <strong>On getting the required 40,000 donors to get on the debate stage:</strong></p><p> Well, we&#39;re gonna be on the debate stage because we&#39;re entrepreneurs, and we&#39;ve got the resources to make it happen. But it&#39;s a goofy rule, and I&#39;m not sure what problem they were trying to solve. But it&#39;s just a question of, what&#39;s your tolerance for cost of acquisition? 。 。 。 I guess they&#39;re eliminating people that either don&#39;t have the resources or don&#39;t have the ingenuity to understand how to do that. If competition is good for America, good for the Republican Party, and whether it&#39;s Asa [Hutchinson] or anybody else, having a broader set of ideas early in the primary would seem to be part of the American tradition. So it&#39;s a clubhouse rule from the RNC. We&#39;ll cross it, we&#39;ll be there.</p><p> <strong>On his pathway to the presidency:</strong></p><p> I think at some point, Republicans are going to decide who has the best chance of beating <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">Joe Biden</a> . And that&#39;s the position that we want to demonstrate that we&#39;re in, because we&#39;re running a campaign where it&#39;s not about, hey, we&#39;re going to win Iowa or just win New Hampshire. I mean, you know, you guys have all the data—Santorum and Cruz and Huckabee all won Iowa and they didn&#39;t win the nomination. We&#39;re trying to win the White House in November of 2024. We understand that this critical juncture in time, that the leadership really matters, leadership that understands the global economy, understands technology, understands what working families are going through, actually cares about the country, has got a track record of—you know, in North Dakota, we treat the taxpayers like they&#39;re customers. There&#39;s so much we can do to reduce the size and scope of the two million federal employees just by having a business mind-set around how you actually get it focused on what it really needs to do.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 20:03:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/doug-burgum-on-the-record-north-dakota-china-energy-tech-2024-3f32b2ec</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/doug-burgum-on-the-record-north-dakota-china-energy-tech-2024-3f32b2ec<category> governor</category><category> north dakota</category><category> china</category><category> energy policy</category><category> coal</category><category> culture war</category><category> carbon emissions</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>Software</category><category> Applications Software</category><category>计算</category><category>技术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Regional Politics</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>regional politics</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>software</category><category> applications software</category><category> computing</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Down the Old Dixie Highway Through the Cradle of the Civil War]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A flat tire forced us off the road, but some genuine Southern hospitality made the detour worthwhile. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10098652755748144108404589653201770322652"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10098652755748144108404589653201770322652"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Daniel Lee</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 4:01 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/down-the-old-dixie-highway-through-the-cradle-of-the-civil-war-road-trip-6aa5a4c6"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821702?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Stephens Garage in Luverne, Ala.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Daniel Lee</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <em>Luverne, Ala.</em></p><p> Just south of this rural county seat along US 331, a dispiriting bong-bong-bong and a dashboard warning light alerted us to that bane of vacation-season travelers: a tire going flat along the roadway. It might not seem a great place to break down. There&#39;s a tongue-in-cheek Internet meme these days featuring an illustrated map of the US with comical state stereotypes and the Deep South walled off as “The DO NOT TRAVEL Zone.”</p><p> More ominously, the NAACP and two LGBT organizations issued “travel advisories” earlier this year, darkly suggesting that Florida Gov. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">Ron DeSantis</a> &#39;s effort to remove critical race theory and discussion of adult sexuality from classrooms puts travelers at risk.</p><p> A lot of people are in transit during the summer, many of them Midwesterners like me, headed to the beaches of Florida, trusting the nation&#39;s modern road system, with its well-lit rest stops, travel plazas and full complement of familiar fast-food outlets every 20 miles or so. Compare that with a century ago, when much travel south was by way of the old Dixie Highway, an early-automobile-era skein of roads connecting the Midwest with Florida.</p><p> Following the Dixie Highway&#39;s distinctive red-and-white DH signs, Yankee tourists bounced through ragged back roads in the South, camping out along the way, fording overflowing streams, repairing their own breakdowns and saying howdy to the locals. Mind you, this was with Union Gen. William Tecumseh Sherman&#39;s incendiary march through the region still a living memory. The Dixie Highway was promoted not only as a commercial and travel necessity, but as a unifying effort. “The meandering, unpaved routes,” College of Charleston historian Tammy Ingram wrote in a 2014 book on the Dixie Highway, were intended as “symbols of modern-day progress that would heal the lingering wounds of the Civil War.”</p><p> When our tire alarm went off, we limped back to Luverne—pronounced <em>Loo</em> -verne, population about 2,500—and found Stephens Garage. The lot was gridlocked with cars, trucks and tractors in every imaginable state of disrepair. Inside, a mounted deer head kept watch over a display of hunting supplies. A padlock served as the front door&#39;s security apparatus. Boxes of 5.56 ammunition suitable for AR-15-style rifles were stacked above motor industry T-shirts and camouflage baseball caps. The setting might have unnerved some of my neighbors up north.</p><p> Stephens Garage is a family-owned business, and on the afternoon we arrived, it seemed the whole family was there. The matriarch, a smiling woman of 50 or so, took us under her wing as soon as we explained our problem. She pulled a workman off another job to check our tire.</p><p> “Can we get these folks back on the road?”她说。 “They&#39;re driving down to the beach.” A daughter-in-law smiled out from behind the counter in the business office, where she was seeing to paperwork with a baby girl strapped across her chest. A son attended to other things, then took the baby for a while. A grizzled guy at the parts counter talked an African-American woman through repairs made to her weed-eater and helped maneuver the thing out the door. As we waited, we listened as the mom gave an apparently elderly and puzzled customer instructions over the phone on how to check the oil in his car.</p><p> “That&#39;s OK. You just bring it up to the shop and we&#39;ll do it for you, honey,” she ended. Soon after, word came back on our tire. “Just needs a plug,” the matriarch told us. “You&#39;re lucky. Some other folks today needed a new clutch. We had to order it.”</p><p> It was good news, but a greater relief was that we had fallen among nice people. Unfortunately, many assume a pleasant and helpful person is masking a certain poverty of character and a lack of respect for progressive social theories. Hospitality and friendliness is regarded as phony, as though a brusque demeanor is a marker for honesty.</p><p> The old MTV reality show “The Real World” asked what would happen when “people stop being polite and start getting real.” If memory serves, what happened was that everything from harsh words to heavy furniture flew and the cast split into warring factions.</p><p> The Dixie Highway was far from a smooth journey geographically or politically. But it merged North and South “in a quintessentially modern monument to national unity,” according to Ms. Ingram. In 1915, the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NYT" class="company-name">New York Times</a></p> called it “the Dixie Peaceway” and christened it a symbol of an “accord between brethren which shall never again be broken.”<p></p><p> The US has traveled a long and unfortunate distance from a bone-jostling network of rugged roads intended to help heal the Union to a sleek system of four- to eight-lane highways that, for all their speed and comfort, can&#39;t seem to keep the nation from pulling itself apart.</p><p> As we were leaving the Stephens family&#39;s garage to get back on the road, I decided to buy a T-shirt and then—as is my tendency—forgot to take it with me. They mailed it to me. That was nice of them.</p><p> <em>Mr. Lee is an Indianapolis writer.</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
